{
  "answer": "The riddling poem known as *The Ruin* (often identified by its opening line \"Wrætlic is þes wealstan\"), which meditates on the remnants of a once-great city destroyed by time and fate, is found as **Chapter 16** in the *Old English Elegies* collection.[^1]\n\nThis elegy describes the shattered walls, fallen towers, and decayed bathhouses of a Roman-era city (likely inspired by Bath), evoking its former splendor—crowded mead-halls, gleaming treasures, and steaming baths—now overtaken by \"Wyrd\" (fate).[^2] The poem's fragmentary and enigmatic style, with vivid ubi sunt (\"where are they?\") reflections on transience, gives it a riddling quality, as the subject (the ruined city) emerges gradually from the imagery.[^3]\n\nHere is the opening of the modern English translation:\n\n> Wondrous is this wall-stone, by Wyrd broken;  \n> Strongholds shattered, the work of giants crumbles.  \n> Roofs are toppled, towers in ruin...[^4]\n\nThe full original Old English text begins:\n\n> Wrætlic is þes wealstan, wyrde gebræcon...[^5]\n\n[^1]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 16 (\"Wraetlic is thes wealstan...\"), [chapter](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/16-wraetlic-is-thes-wealstan-wyrde-yebraecon-burgsted/translation/).\n\n[^2]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 16, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/16-wraetlic-is-thes-wealstan-wyrde-yebraecon-burgsted/translation/#p-ba51da).\n\n[^3]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 16, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/16-wraetlic-is-thes-wealstan-wyrde-yebraecon-burgsted/translation/#p-dfdbda).\n\n[^4]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 16, [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/16-wraetlic-is-thes-wealstan-wyrde-yebraecon-burgsted/translation/#p-d0d2bd).\n\n[^5]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 16, [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/16-wraetlic-is-thes-wealstan-wyrde-yebraecon-burgsted/original/#p-ab68b4).",
